node.text:
Who has Zion National Park on their bucket list? Save this post for recommendations from a Utah native and Delta Medallion 📲

"I’ve visited Zion National Park more times than I can count - and it’s still my favorite Utah national park.

What should you do while you’re there?
- Angels Landing / The Narrows - these are both incredibly popular hikes for a good reason. I’ve done both several times. Start EARLY!
- Explore the east side of Zion. Less visitors, no shuttles and more access. I’ve spent so much time on this side of the park in the last year and loved every second of it.
- Go canyoneering. I can’t believe I spent 6 years in Utah before trying this and I already can’t wait to do it again.
- Explore the areas just outside the park. The amazing scenery doesn’t end with the park boundaries. In fact, the nearby options often bring much smaller crowds and really impressive views." - @andreafcannon, Diamond Medallion Member

Have Zion recs to add to our list? Leave them below ⬇️

"I grew up white, Jewish, and gay in the South. And while coming into the world none of those things were within my control – they were my 'given circumstances,' so to speak – each plays a crucial role in my identity. The first was physically impossible to hide, the second I hid selectively, the third I tried to conceal completely until I was eighteen years old, and the last is merely environment, but still impactful. 

I think it’s important to understand that people in the LGBTQ+ community, like any marginalized community, are likely to experience events of significant trauma. And yet despite such tangible adversity, members of the LGBTQ+ community rally around each other with an enviable degree of strength and love. To the untrained eye, Pride may seem like a bunch of rainbows, glitter and unicorns, but in fact it is an expression of a collective perseverance. 

When I tell you what about being a gay man makes me most proud, I’m not only speaking to my own process of overcoming hardship, I’m also celebrating the resolve of those standing beside me today and the countless nameless others that came before me so that I may stand on their shoulders. That is what Pride is about. And one day, someone else will stand on my shoulders, and we will be that much closer to a truly equitable tomorrow." Braden J. - Marketing Product Leader, #ATL 

Pride is about hope, resilience and acceptance. By supporting each other through adversity, we can help create a future that treats everyone equally.
